AGI -&nbsp;The trial hearings for alleged money laundering against Panamanian law firm Mossack Fonseca, epicentre of the international scandal "Panama Papers", and another twenty defendants concluded in Panama. The sentence will be announced in the coming weeks. Judge Baloisa Marquinez took advantage of the term of 30 working days imposed by the Panamanian law to issue his verdict. The public prosecutor Isis Soto asked for 12 years in prison, the maximum penalty for money laundering, for Jurgen Mossack and Ramon Fonseca, founders of the company protagonist of the scandal that broke out in 2016. "There was really a great injustice that was committed, not only to me, but to all the people who worked with me, who are many," said Mossack at the end of the hearing. "I repeat that both my partner and all the people who have worked with me have been serious, honest and correct people," he added. Soto also asked for 5 to 12 years of imprisonment for another 24 defendants, mostly former employees of the company. The process began eight years after the International Consortium of Investigative Journalists (ICIJ) published the "Panama Papers" on April 3, 2016. This investigation, based on millions of documents from the Mossack Fonseca law firm, revealed how personalities from around the world hid property, businesses, assets and profits to evade taxes or recycle money. To do so, they created opaque companies, through Mossack Fonseca, to open bank accounts and create convenient foundations in multiple countries with the aim of hiding money, in some cases from illegal activities. Vladimir Putin, but also the former rulers of Iceland, Sigmundur David Gunnlaugsson; from Pakistan, Nawaz Sharif; from Britain, David Cameron; and from Argentina Mauricio Macri; besides the Argentine football star Lionel Messi are some of the names mentioned in the Papers.
&nbsp;
"Mrs Jurgen Mossack and Ramon Fonseca have received and transferred funds from illegal activities in Germany and Argentina," said the public prosecutor Soto during the trial. According to the prosecution, Mossack, 76, and Fonseca, 71, are responsible for facilitating through the law firm the creation of opaque companies in which directors of the German multinational Siemens deposited millions of euros outside the real accounting of the company. That "box B" would be served to hide the money from the payment of fees. The Panamanian office, according to the charge, would also be used to mass money from a massive scam in Argentina. However, Guillermina McDonald, Mossack's lawyer and other defendants, told AFP that the trial presents "defects" and "nullity profiles". "If there is justice, they should be acquitted, not only because no punishable act or connection of our clients has been demonstrated, but because the process is null," Mc Donald added. Ramon Fonseca didn't show up at the hearings because he was hospitalized. Because of the scandal, the company Mossack Fonseca closed its doors, while the international image of Panama, accused of being a tax haven, was seriously affected. After the "Panama Papers" the country carried out some legal reforms, which allowed him to leave the "grey list" of the Financial Action Task Force (GAFI) in 2023. "A conviction would be a different and new judicial precedent, but with less practical impact today because regulatory changes have already occurred in the last eight years," Carlos Barsallo, former president of the Panamanian section of NGO Transparency International. However, "if there was no conviction, the international community would hardly understand and prejudices on Panama would end up finding confirmation." &nbsp;

